            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "Will just leave a note that I also found this issue now after being slightly surprised by the behavior when passing `contents =` just now in the context of writing a plugin which helps with finding test files across different languages given a source file (https://github.com/Julian/runt.nvim/), i.e. it implements \"tell me the file path of the test file which corresponds to some file\". In particular I know I do want an API that gets better results when a buffer is open containing the source file, but I also want an API that operates without that, for cases where a user directly wants to open a test file (without getting too far in the weeds on the workflow specifics). But in order to decide on language-specific behavior for where test files live, it was useful to use `vim.filetype.match` to get a filetype from the source file path, and the current behavior means I get to implement effectively what was described above about scratch buffers manually instead of e.g. reading in the contents of the source path and passing those along for the match.\n\n(I'm not saying that in my opinion that means this justifies the complexity to support, just sharing my use case for taking into the equation).",
